The '''100 years of women in transport''' campaign (YOWIT) is a celebration of the significant role that women have played in the transport industry over the past 100 years in the [[United Kingdom]], following the centennial anniversary of the [[First World War]], when 100,000 women entered the [[transport]] industry to take on the responsibilities held by men who enlisted for military service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/public-leaders-network/2014/nov/08/world-war-women-workplace-public-services|title=Women in wartime: the rise of the female public servant|author =Sarah Dawood|website=the Guardian}}</ref><ref>http://www.ltmuseum.co.uk/assets/downloads/pdfs/Yearbook_2014-15_optimised.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infrastructure-intelligence.com/article/jun-2014/first-100-years-women-transport|title=The first 100 years of women in transport|website=Infrastructure Intelligence}}</ref>
The programme is a partnership between [[Transport for London]], the [[Department for Transport]] (DfT), [[Crossrail]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crossrail.co.uk/news/articles/crossrail-partners-with-women-into-construction|title=Crossrail partners with Women into Construction|website=Crossrail}}</ref> [[Network Rail]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkrail.co.uk/Digital_Archive_Blog.aspx?id=30064794570&blogid=30064773519&author=Vicky|title=Network Rail -|website=networkrail.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onemk.co.uk/news/2015/6/network-rail-senior-manager-shares-experiences-26767427.html |title=NETWORK RAIL: Senior manager shares her experiences to celebrate 100 years of women in transport |website=MK News }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Women's Engineering Society]](WES)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wes.org.uk/100yowit|title=100 Years of Women in Transport|website=wes.org.uk}}</ref> and the Women’s Transportation Seminar (WTS).<ref name="transportforlondon,windsorhouse,42-50victoriastreet,londonsw1h0tl,enquire@tfl.gov.uk">{{cite web|url=https://tfl.gov.uk/campaign/100-years-of-women-in-transport|title=100 Years of Women in Transport|author=Transport for London|website=tfl.gov.uk|access-date=14 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160119235035/https://tfl.gov.uk/campaign/100-years-of-women-in-transport|archive-date=19 January 2016|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.london.gov.uk/get-involved/events/100-years-of-women-in-transport|title=100 Years of Women in Transport|website=london.gov.uk|access-date=14 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151005165301/http://www.london.gov.uk/get-involved/events/100-years-of-women-in-transport|archive-date=5 October 2015|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
In 2015, the campaign raised awareness to the low representation of females in this industry<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transporttimes.co.uk/news.php/MORE-WOMEN-ARE-NEEDED-TO-JOIN-OUR-INDUSTRY-64/|title=Transport Times Events - News/Blog - MORE WOMEN ARE NEEDED TO JOIN OUR INDUSTRY|website=transporttimes.co.uk}}</ref> by commemorating the 100 years of [[Maida Vale tube station]] (the first to be fully staffed by women),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/london/2015-06-06/maida-vale-station-marks-100th-anniversary/|title=Maida Vale station marks 100th anniversary|website=ITV News}}</ref> and holding a debate competition between year 9 students from 30 schools across the UK with engineering and construction company, Bechtel. The winning team was composed by four girls from [[St Marylebone School]].<ref>https://tfl.gov.uk/info-for/media/press-releases/2015/december/st-marylebone-school-named-winner-of-100-years-of-women-in-transport-debate</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newsoneplace.com/article/7962791509/uk-nov-school-children-debate-women-transport# |title=Archived copy |access-date=27 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208021255/http://www.newsoneplace.com/article/7962791509/uk-nov-school-children-debate-women-transport# |archive-date=8 February 2016 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>http://article.wn.com/view/2015/12/02/St_Marylebone_School_named_winner_of_100_Years_of_Women_in_T/</ref>
The programme also profiled several women that are currently in the industry to showcase the variety of careers available within transport.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tfl.gov.uk/campaign/women-in-transport-profiles|title=Women in transport profiles|author=Transport for London|website=tfl.gov.uk|access-date=3 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204151600/https://tfl.gov.uk/campaign/women-in-transport-profiles|archive-date=4 February 2016|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.morson.com/investing-in-our-future-women-in-engineering/|title=Investing in Our Future - Women in Engineering|website=Morson}}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.womanthology.co.uk/mind-gender-gap-tricia-riley-hr-director-transport-london-tfl-positive-outlook-gender-balance/|title=Mind the [Gender] Gap: Tricia Riley, HR Director at TfL has a positive outlook on gender balance - Womanthology|website=Womanthology}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtsinternational.org/london//past-events/100-years-of-women-in-transport/|title=Launch of 100 Years of Women in Transport|website=wtsinternational.org}}</ref>
In November 2015, the campaign celebrated 100 years since the first female bus conductor, Ms G. Duncan, started to work in London on 1 November 1915.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/13931087.Bus_drivers_mark_100_years_since_London_s_first_female_bus_conductor_started_work/|title=Bus drivers mark 100 years since London's first female bus conductor started work|website=Your Local Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southwarknews.co.uk/news-category/transport/|title=Transport|website=Southwark News}}</ref>
