{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Board of Audit |nativename = 会計検査院 |nativename_r = Kaikeikensain |abbreviation = |logo = |logo_width = |logo_caption = |seal = File:Board of Audit JAPAN seal.png |seal_width = 200px |seal_caption = Board of Audit seal (created 1881) |formed = 1880 |jurisdiction = {{JPN}} |headquarters = 3-2-2 [[Kasumigaseki]], [[Chiyoda, Tokyo|Chiyoda-ku]], [[Tokyo]] 100-8941, [[Japan]] |employees = 1,277 (as of January 2011) with approximately 970 engaged in audit work |budget = |chief1_name = Mitsuhiko Kawado |chief1_position = President |chief2_name = Dr. Mari Kobayashi |chief2_position = Commissioner |chief3_name = Yūji Morita |chief3_position = Commissioner |chief4_name = Okamura Hajime |chief4_position = Secretary General |chief5_name = Kensuke Koshiyama |chief5_position = Deputy Secretary General |parent_agency = [[Government of Japan]] |website = [http://www.jbaudit.go.jp/ Official website] |footnotes = }}
The {{Nihongo|'''Board of Audit'''|会計検査院|Kaikeikensain}} reviews government expenditures and submits an annual report to the [[National Diet|Diet]]. Article 90 of the [[Constitution of Japan]] and the Board of Audit Act of 1947 give this body substantial independence from both [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]] and [[Diet of Japan|Diet]] control.
In 1968, it hosted the [[International Congress of Supreme Audit Institutions|INCOSAI]] VI, the sixth triennial convention of the [[International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions]].<ref>{{citation | title = [[:File:INTOSAI 50 Years.pdf|INTOSAI: 50 Years (1953-2003)]] | publisher = [[International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions]] | year = 2004 | location = [[Vienna, Austria|Vienna]] | page = 49}}</ref>
The headquarters is located at 3-2-2 Kasumigaseki, Chiyoda-ku, Tokyo 100-8941, Japan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Board of Audit website|url=http://www.jbaudit.go.jp/english/index.html|publisher=Board of Audit|accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref>
== History == The origins of the Board of Audit can be traced back to a division established in 1869 under the [[Daijō-kan]]. It was reorganized as an auditing organ under the Daijō-kan in 1880.<ref name="Board of Audit | History">{{cite web|title=History of the Board|url=http://www.jbaudit.go.jp/english/jbaudit/history.html|website=Board of Audit of Japan}}</ref>
Article 90 of the [[Constitution of Japan|Constitution of 1947]] states: "Final accounts of the expenditures and revenues of the State shall be audited annually by a Board of Audit and submitted by the Cabinet to the Diet, together with the statement of audit, during the fiscal year immediately following the period covered." The original Japanese uses the word ''subete'' to indicate that all state expenditures and revenues are subject to audit. In 2013, the [[Abe Shinzō|Abe government]] tried to circumvent this under the [[State Secrecy Law]], but relented in 2015.{{sfn|Jones|2016}}
