{{elections}}

'''Redistribution''' is the process, used in many Commonwealth countries, by which electoral districts are added, removed, or otherwise changed. Redistribution is a form of [[boundary delimitation]] that changes [[electoral district]] boundaries, usually in response to periodic census results.<ref name = ACE>[http://aceproject.org/ace-en/topics/bd/bdz01 Boundary Delimitation Glossary] ACE:The Electoral Knowledge Network. Accessed 4 July 2009.</ref> Redistribution is required by law or constitution at least every decade in most [[representative democracy]] systems that use [[first-past-the-post]] or similar electoral systems to prevent geographic [[malapportionment]]. The act of manipulation of electoral districts to favour a candidate or party is called [[gerrymandering]].

==Australia==
{{Main|Redistribution (Australia)}}
In Australia, redistributions are carried out by independent and non-partisan commissioners in the [[Commonwealth]], and in each state or territory. The various electoral acts require the population of each seat to be equal, within certain strictly limited variations. The longest period between two redistributions can be no greater than seven years.  Many other triggers can force redistribution before the chronological limit is reached. The redistribution is drafted by civil servants.

==Canada==
{{Main|Electoral district (Canada)#Boundary adjustment}}
In Canada, the constitution mandates that redistribution occur "on the completion of each decennial census."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canlii.org/en/ca/laws/stat/30---31-vict-c-3/latest/30---31-vict-c-3.html|title= The Constitution Act, 1867 (UK), 30 & 31 Victoria, c 3, Section 51 (1) |publisher=[[Canadian Legal Information Institute]] |accessdate=25 August 2013 |date=1 April 1999}}</ref> District boundaries are based on electoral quotients, with some exceptions. When the census indicates that a population change has occurred, an independent boundary commission issues a report of recommended changes.  Changes are only made if passed into law—by Parliament for national redistribution, by the provincial legislature for provincial redistribution.

==India==

India has an established process to redistribute its legislative districts. Redistributions are approved by political appointees to the [[Boundary Commission of India]].

==Ireland==
{{further|Constituency Commission}}
The [[Constitution of Ireland]] states that general elections to the [[Dáil]] (lower house) must use the [[single transferable vote]] (STV), that each [[Dáil constituency]] must return at least three members ([[Teachta Dála|TD]]s), that boundaries must be revised at least every twelve years, and that the ratio of TDs to inhabitants (not voters or citizens) be between 20,000 and 30,000 on average and "so far as it is practicable" equal between constituencies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/en/constitution/index.html#article16|title=Constitution Of Ireland |page=Article 16 |nopp=Y |accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref> [[:Category:Electoral Acts (Ireland)|Electoral Acts]] are passed by the [[Oireachtas]] to revise boundaries in light of the most recent census.<ref name="FordeLeonard2013">{{cite book |last1=Forde |first1=Michael |last2=Leonard |first2=David |title=Constitutional Law of Ireland |date=2013 |publisher=A&C Black |isbn=9781847667380 |pages=§§21.05–21.08 |nopp=Y |edition=3rd |url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=YVsQAgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA606&ots=FaEsCwTjiE&dq=constituency%20population%20unconstitutional%2030000&pg=PA605#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=1 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In constituencies for the [[Next Irish general election|next general election]], the 2016 population per TD averages 29,762, varying from 28,199 in [[Dublin North-West (Dáil constituency)|Dublin North-West]] to 31,270 in [[Dún Laoghaire (Dáil constituency)|Dún Laoghaire]].<ref>{{cite book |author1=Constituency Commission |title=Constituency Commission Report 2017: Dáil and European Parliament Constituencies |date=2017 |publisher=Stationery Office |location=Dublin |isbn=978-1-4064-2952-7 |page=66 |url=http://www.constituency-commission.ie/docs/Constituency%20Commission%20Report%202017.pdf#page=68 |format=PDF |chapter=Appendix 2: Statistics relating to recommended Dáil constituencies}}; {{cite web |title=Electoral (Amendment) (Dáil Constituencies) Bill 2017: Second Stage |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/seanad/2017-12-15/10/ |website=Seanad Éireann debate |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=2 October 2018 |language=en-ie |date=15 December 2017}}; {{cite web |title=Electoral (Amendment) (Dáil Constituencies) Act 2017 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/2017/act/39/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book |accessdate=2 October 2018 |language=en |date=23 December 2017}}</ref> Since 1977, an independent body (since 1997 a permanent [[Constituency Commission]]) recommends boundaries, which the Oireachtas usually accepts.<ref name="FordeLeonard2013"/> The terms of reference of the Commission have set five seats as the maximum and discourage constituencies crossing [[counties of Ireland|county]] boundaries.{{#tag:ref|Large counties may be split into multiple constituencies, and small counties paired in a single constituency, but combining part of one county with part or all of another causes controversy.|group="n"}}<ref name="FordeLeonard2013"/>  A separate [[Local Electoral Area Boundary Committee]] fulfils a similar function for [[Local Electoral Area]] boundaries. A proposed [[Electoral Commission (Ireland)|Electoral Commission]] would replace both the Constituency Commission and the Local Electoral Area Boundary Committee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.environ.ie/en/Publications/LocalGovernment/Voting/FileDownLoad,40119,en.pdf  |date=27 January 2015 |title=Consultation Paper on the Establishment of an Electoral Commission in Ireland |format=PDF |publisher=Department of the Environment, Community and Local Government (DECLG) |accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref> 

Before 1977, boundary drawing was often partisan in favour of the government of the day. The Electoral (Amendment) Act 1959 was struck out in 1961 by the [[Supreme Court (Ireland)|Supreme Court]] as being repugnant to the Constitution because of excessive [[malapportionment]].<ref name="FordeLeonard2013"/>  The replacement [[Electoral (Amendment) Act 1961]] relied on [[Issues affecting the single transferable vote#District size|manipulating district size]]{{#tag:ref|Where the [[Fianna Fáil]] party of [[Government of the 16th Dáil|the then government]] had less than 50% support, four-seat constituencies were used, so that Fianna Fáil would win two of four seats; where it had more than 50% support, three- or five-seat constituencies would give it two of three, or three of five.<ref name="Parker1986">{{cite journal|last=Parker|first=A. J.|year=1986|title=Geography and the Irish Electoral System|journal=Irish Geography|volume=19|issue=1|pages=1–14|issn=0075-0778|doi=10.1080/00750778609478835}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Harrop|first1=Martin|last2=Miller|first2=William Lockley|title=Elections and voters: a comparative introduction|date=1987|publisher=Macmillan Education|isbn=9780333347607|page=65}}<!--|accessdate=28 April 2015--></ref>|group="n"}} The Supreme Court allowed the 1961 act, ruling that the Oireachtas had wide latitude to decide what degree of divergence was "practicable" and what factors could be considered, but reserved the right to [[judicial review]] of proposed boundaries.<ref name="FordeLeonard2013"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.supremecourt.ie/supremecourt/sclibrary3.nsf/%28WebFiles%29/CD7B68D9BC678262802575F3002D42C6/$FILE/Electoral%201961_%5B1961%5D%20IR%20169.htm#footnote_1|title=In re Art. 26 of the Constitution and the Electoral (Amendment) Bill, 1961.|work=[1961] I.R. 169|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref>  [[Third Amendment of the Constitution Bill 1968|A 1968 proposal]] rejected by referendum would have specified one-sixth as the maximum constituency divergence from the average population per TD. [[Fourth Amendment of the Constitution Bill 1968|Another proposal]], rejected simultaneously, would have established a constituency commission (ancillary to replacing STV with [[first-past-the-post voting]]). The [[Electoral (Amendment) Act 1974]] attempted a manipulation similar to the 1961 act, but backfired when a larger than expected [[Swing (politics)|swing]] created a tipping point favouring the opposition [[Irish general election, 1977|in 1977]]. There was a lacuna after the publication of the 2016 census results in which the [[Electoral (Amendment) (Dáil Constituencies) Act 2013]] was in force but its 158 seats breached the 30,000 population average; jurists wondered whether the courts would have permitted a general election in the interim before the [[Electoral (Amendment) (Dáil Constituencies) Act 2017]] resolved the issue.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carolan |first1=Mary |title=Next Dáil 'unconstitutional' if number of TDs not increased |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/courts/high-court/next-d%C3%A1il-unconstitutional-if-number-of-tds-not-increased-1.3308193 |accessdate=1 October 2018 |work=The Irish Times |date=28 November 2017}}; {{cite web |last1=O'Mahony |first1=Conor |last2=Ó Conaill |first2=Seán |title=Not Just a Christmas Election – An Unconstitutional Election? |url=http://constitutionproject.ie/?p=644 |website=Constitution Project |publisher=UCC |accessdate=1 October 2018 |date=27 November 2017}}</ref>

==Japan==
Japan does not have an established process to redistribute its legislative districts. The frequency of redistributions is irregular and not triggered a particular event. Redistributions are approved by the national legislature.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}

==New Zealand==
New Zealand has a fixed process to determine how its legislative districts are redistributed. Redistribution in New Zealand happens every five years following the census.<ref name="New Zealand">{{Cite web| title=Calculating future Māori and General Electorates &#124; Electoral Commission |url=http://www.elections.org.nz/voting-system/electorates/electorate-boundaries-and-review/calculating-future-maori-and-general |date=18 November 2013 |accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref>

==Philippines==
In the Philippines, redistricting is carried out by [[Congress of the Philippines|Congress]] after every decennial census is published. However, Congress has never passed a general redistricting act, and instead redistricts provinces or cities piecemeal, or creates new provinces or cities with legislative districts. The last general redistricting law was via the ordinance in the 1987 constitution, which was based from the 1980 census. The creation of a new province or city needs the approval of the public via a [[plebiscite]], while piecemeal redistricting does not need a plebiscite.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}

==United Kingdom==
{{Main|Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)}}

In the United Kingdom, there are four Boundary Commissions (one each for England, Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland) responsible for reviewing the boundaries of Parliamentary constituencies. Members of Boundary Commissions are political appointees.

==United States==
{{Main|Redistricting}}

In the United States, redistribution occurs after each decennial census. Most states' legislative district redistributions are approved by the state legislature. [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] rulings (such as the [[One_man,_one_vote#United_States|one man, one vote]] principle) require that legislative districts have roughly equal populations.

